The moral here is: Humans deliver healthcare and humans are imperfect. The rate of medication error is 1 in 10 administrations. People work hard behind the scenes to prevent error by improving processes not punishing people. The vaccine rollout should be no exception.

Priority 3 is system improvement. In this case, we removed that particular formulation from the ward.In other cases, drugs with similar names were placed on different shelves, drugs with similar vials were marked with coloured stickers/extra labelling.

Priority 2 is staff wellbeing. The nurse was gutted. I thanked them for recognising the error and escalating. I was explicit about our no-blame culture. I made sure they were emotionally supported.Medication errors are never intentional.I feel for the doc in this situation.

Priority 1 is patient safety! We made sure the patient was well, their vitals were normal and the ‚Äòantidote‚Äô was available and charted. We transferred them to another ward for closer monitoring.In the process, we explained what had happened and apologised.

Here‚Äôs a bedtime story about medication safety to frame the vaccine ‚Äòoverdose‚Äô, and channel the attention away from blame and toward change.Once upon a time, the ward phoned me to tell me a nurse had administered a painkiller to my patient at a dose 10x that was prescribed.

Today Nisha is a beloved pediatrician at a community clinic called BronxDocs, a Big Brother Big Sister, check this inspiring video:  https://t.co/poygSDXGKF and sharing many talents, like breadmaking :) Thank you Nisha for all you do for the world 10/10

Nisha ultimately went on to Columbia medical school, but not before also doing the work to author papers on Lassa fever and tuberculosis, and on our study of susceptibility to Lassa fever a decade in the making 9/10

But Nisha carried on & kept me going. We traveled to Nigeria, together with Christian Happi and his team, and my mom. We took the long road to Irrua, Nigeria, one of the epicenters of Lassa fever and research, and we launched our program still strong today 8/10

Nisha stumbled on the 1969 @Yale Lassa outbreak https://t.co/bL6o5dVOm5 Shook, we then realized that Joe was 14 days in a tent with Ebola patients-Joe from #thehotzone While Still our hero, it did change our perception of what Joe called safe  7/10

We wrote our first grant to the @gatesfoundation hoping to convince them Lassa fever needed attention & it was a public health crisis but overshadowed by its label as a bioterrorist threat. They weren‚Äôt convinced. We kept trying 6/10

We became Joe McCormick superfans & through Nisha‚Äôs initiative we got to work with him. Nisha developed a Lassa virus-recombinant-nuclear protein based IgG-ELISA test before connecting w/ Tulane. We were so grateful to have stumbled on such an important challenge 5/10

Lassa appeared to us to be the most important virus in human history, and one of the current greatest natural and bioterrorist threats, and yet so little was known about. Along the way, we learned the stories, and have many of our own 4/10

Together we embarked on the study of Lassa fever, first discovered in Nigeria, and likely to have been an ancient and still deadly threat there. Nisha & I pored through 40-years of literature on Lassa virus and became more fascinated at each step 3/10

Nisha was the first official member of the @sabeti_lab. An inspiring @Harvard systems biology PhD student who had decided after a personal experience to become a doctor just as I joined faculty. We had one amazing year before she would go off to start her clinical journey 2/10

In #blackhistorymonth I have reflected on the extraordinary contributions of black scientists as well as on the amazing alumni & current @sabeti_lab members & the impact they have had on my lab‚Äôs history, starting with Dr. Nisha Broodie. 1/10

There were a couple larger plants in it's family with the great fruit taste too.I'll be growing out several plants from each of the batches of seed I collected from these plants.

The plant also had the short stature I was looking for. This isn't ideal for growing a the grassy garden edge where I planted it, but would be great for growing in pots.This plant was a total outlier from it's family, so I can only hope some of its progeny will be similar.

When it fruited, I ended up eating almost all of them straight off the plant. The small fruit tasted -much- better than any I'd experienced.Almost every flower resulted in a fruit and there were more flowers than I'd seen before on that size plant.T

The next season I'll grow out a batch of those F2 seeds to see what happens.Last year I was screening a few F2 populations looking for dwarf and miniature stature plants.One plant had large flower clusters open even before I had it in the ground. I kept an eye on that one.

Part of my #PlantBreeding strategy is to just mix things up and see what happens. It is common for unexpected traits to emerge, things which result from the combination of parental genetics but where hidden in the parents.When an unexpected hybrid arises I'll save it's seeds.

And, perhaps, those responsible for the regulation and/or legislation for social media should be pulled from those with a proven track record of foresight, with minimal participation in promulgating societal harm - rather than those who willingly profit from said manipulation.

At minimum, there needs to be a clearinghouse for the risks posed by technology, where any employees and all citizens can report their concerns, publicly accessible, which can be cited in legislation or litigation, or regulation... like a bug bounty for interaction design.

It's about ensuring that every design decision to drive engagement is met with a full analysis of the potential benefits AND risks - and that businesses are liable for both any forseeable - AND unforseen but forseeable by SOMEONE.

This isn't "cancel culture" - it's about extending trust to those who can be trusted; it's about extending responsibility to those who have not ignored, and have acted to mitigate the risk of harm in the work they do, or to stop doing the work.

I hope that developers think more about accessibility and I hope that this also involves consideration on how to reduce motion sickness triggers. Thank you to @CanIPlayThat for providing a platform to make games more inclusive. 8/8

What I do to reduce motion sickness: Play on easy (fewer dodging etc. required), play ranged characters, play Switch games on the console, use a small computer monitor, don‚Äôt play games I want to play. Watching others play isn‚Äôt an option since it‚Äòs even worse. 7/8
What helps with motion sickness: Camera fixed behind character, not having to roll and dodge in fights or general fast movements of my character, FOV settings (only a bit). 6/8

What makes motion sickness worse: Independent movement of camera and character, head bobbing, caves, narrow corridors, in general larger things that move in front of the camera and block my view of the horizon. 5/8

Games I would love to play but can‚Äôt play at all or just for very short times: @CyberpunkGame, @witchergame, @ConanExiles, Minecraft (yep, it‚Äòs not an issue of realistic graphics), Left4Dead, Skyrim, Breath of the Wild and countless others. 4/8
For me, motion sickness includes dizziness, headache, nausea and sudden burst of cold sweat. These symptoms can persist half an hour or longer even after I stopped playing. 3/8

My favorite games are strategy games like Northgard, card games like @PlayHearthstone and @PlayRuneterra, iso perspective RPGs like @Diablo. Why? Because they don‚Äòt trigger my motion sickness as almost all first person and plenty of third person games do. 2/8

So, each household gets an allowance, where rates are stabilized to within 10%...And any overages get billed out at a 10^6 increase, before getting cut off.Or something like that.It can be made to work.

And, sorry, but that means utilities are gonna have to cut off the juice if Bunny wants to heat up her hot room to do Bikram in the middle of a Polar vortex...  Meeting everyone's basic threshold for survival comes first.
But when the issue is lack of heat instead of excess, it's only going to be survivable for everybody if everybody is on the same playing field.

And in the 2 weeks after Katrina, I survived on a 12-volt deep cycle battery w/solar trickle charger to power one fan and one lamp, and went somewhere else during the day for computer and phone power.It's survivable.  Read a book.
I've lived in pretty rural places, so I know how this goes.I've gone w/o water for weeks when wells run dry in winter.W/o heat (& water) in winter when the electricity goes out really sucks.
No fridges, no baking, no hot tubs, no pools.  Use those, and it cuts into your heating budget.And this goes for EVERYONE.  Even those in Ted Cruz's 'hood.
Affordances for the elderly and those who have medical conditions.You have smart meters. use 'em.

In emergencies, throttle your customers - allocate a set number of KwH to customers based on the requirements for a) maintaining a livable environment (55-64F) & b) minimizing the risk of damage to unoccupied property if excess avail.  Heat plus minimal lighting.  Period.

Scarcity-based pricing models for commodities required for survival would be acceptable if each customer had a base contract for delivery of the minimum electricity required to maintain a location with conditions required to sustain life, with overages subject to fluctuation. https://t.co/VGriAQ6i3a
Texas doesn't have an Energy Reliability Council and a Public Utilities Commission.Texas has an energy racket.And it just killed a bunch of people.

this would incentivize some kind of kickback scheme where the few winterized facilities were encouraging others to NOT winterize, to ensure they would continue to enjoy benefit from future storms.And that puts the people of Texas at even greater risk going forward.

Not only does this not incentivize preparedness, it effectively limits the number of energy providers who will winterize going forward of their own free volition - TBH, with this degree of fuckery afoot,

Instead, the PUC uses what should have been a predictable event to enrich those who DID winterize,  metes no penalty for those who ignored the responsibility, and places all the burden on the consumer.
If all utilities were mandated to winterize in advance, the catastrophe that was thrust upon the people of Texas would not have impacted anywhere near as many households.

I don't care if the PUC authorized a rate hike.An 18,000% increase is not a 'hike.'A two-fold increase in the order of magnitude in something required for survival is NOT a hike.  It's beyond gouging.It's extortion.And the TX PUC is complicit.

Any bills already issued should be comped, and each instance should be counted as a violation.If doubling the price of water during an emergency is considered price gouging, increasing costs on something required for survival by an order of magnitude is certainly price gouging.

My final plea as ever - do not think this is a problem best solved by nations or factions by themselves. It is an all of humanity problem, and it needs all of humanity's innovation and thinking to get out of.

Just like the spring bulbs coming through on my walks I am optimistic - vaccines are the major change in the game - but we will be likely living a more complex life for a while - but one with more friends, family, cheer and enjoyment I hope.

Accepting an endemic endgame is *not* the same as advocating for a "let it rip" as soon as possible (indeed, quite the opposite!). It is more understanding the realistic scenarios of where this will all end up.

(An interesting aside here is one of the current Coronaviruses might well have been responsible for the "Russian Flu" of 1889, with some striking similarities to this pandemic, so as a species we've potentially been through this before)

Where is the endgame of this all? I do think the most likely one is SARS-CoV-2 becoming the 5th endemic human coronavirus, and quite possibly by far the nastiest of the set; we may well be having regular SARS-CoV-2 vaccinations every year (or couple of years)

It will be complex and much of the world is not so old for example - so the risk profiles are different - but there are plenty of people who will really benefit from the vaccine which will also push transmission and new variants down.
This is both a moral imperative - there are lives and livelihoods to be saved - but as important is that the population unit to be concerned about is the world - all humans.
Due to advocacy before the pandemic and fast moving work during it, the @covaxxvaccine and @gavi projects are a forum to help organise and distribute SARS-CoV-2 vaccine worldwide.

This work is the result of a great collaboration between scientists from @HHU_de, @UniklinikDUS, the public health authorities of the city of @Duesseldorf, and Zotz | Klimas (https://t.co/TKl1TZO4mv), a large commercial testing lab.

Future work: What could we learn if we sequenced as high a proportion of local cases as possible (instead of a small proportion), and provided close-to-real-time (instead of retrospective) analytics? We are tying to find out at the moment! https://t.co/4zfjoVmKwG.
Genomics may have an important role to play here, and sequencing can of course help address additional important questions e.g. about the emergence and incidence of variants of concern like B.1.1.7.

One year into the pandemic, it is still not always clear where relevant transmissions in the population actually take place. A better understanding may enable the design of more targeted interventions (e.g. just close X and Y, instead of locking everything down).

Conclusion: Bringing together genomic and routine contact tracing data for analysis by local public health authorities can contribute to an improved characterization of transmission chains in the population.

7) Last, but not least, we showed that genomic data can be generated and relayed to public health authorities in <30h (using @nanopore and hat tip to @MadsAlbertsen85 and @CovidGenomicsUK, who routinle achieve very impressive turnaround times).

6) We integrated routine contact tracing data and found that all 5 genetically identified clusters likely pointed to bona fide transmission chains / clusters - previously known in 4/5 cases, but also including a previously unrecognzed transmission through a local gym.
5) We applied a simple greedy clustering algorithm to the collected surveillance data and found 5 clusters of genetically identical isolates.
Interlude II: So what about transmission chains / clusters in the general population, i.e. involving non-outbreak samples?

We also use the multiple contrast estimands to suggest novel ways of selecting candidate models, e.g. by finding the models which minimize the norm of the treatment effects across many contrasts.

Multiple simultaneous treatments also typically implies multiple estimands of interest.  In some simple settings (e.g. Gaussian outcomes), we characterize the confounder bias as a function of the treatment contrast estimand and inferred latent variable model.

This is particular important with multi-cause inference where there are additional observable implications.  The distn of the confounder given treatments is identifiable in for some LV models.¬† This is still not enough to point identify causal effects, hence the need for s.a.

Our sensitivity analysis uses the Gaussian copula to characterize the conditional dependence between outcome and confounder given treatments. Our approach can be applied to any models of the observables. (" no observable implications", see¬†https://t.co/b3qDa3mAa6)

Here is where 5hmC is now shining new light in early cancer diagnosis. The 5-hydroxymethylation marks are concentrated into 8-12% of the genome, into what people would class as functionally enriched parts of the genome, such as genes (gene bodies), promoters, proximal enhancers

In this way, we take out the "boring" part of a 5mC profile and only include the regions that could maximally inform a healthy vs cancer diagnosis. Another approach is to find a different epigenomic mark that has less of the "boring" part, and not have to design a panel.

One way is to do this in a targetted fashion: only select loci that you think are interesting as part of the biomarker. @GrailBio solved this with the "brute force" approach: spend lots of money doing it genome-wide, then distill the targetted panel from it.

So if pulling down the 5mC fraction of a cfDNA sample is cheaper because it concentrates the throughput in the 50-60% of the genome that is consistently methylated, then what else can be done to further drive down the cost of each #epigenomic profile?

This idea is great in principle but has been difficult to implement for small amounts of DNA. The De Carvalho lab, and their spin-off DNAmx (https://t.co/8WOh2DV0SA) has shown progress on the original work that was done by the Reik Lab in Cambridge UK.

@JGI and @NCBI can help facilitate the right way by adding the name of the PI and the embargo information to all project entries. This information should be immediately apparent. I know @JGI is actively working on data management, and I thank them for that! 3/3

Notes from a 2017 lecture I gave at the @medialab on conceptual art + blockchain, goes into this project in more detail for anyone interested, along with a history of dematerialization and the political economy of artist publishing. https://t.co/l6tSH2i6WI

This is one of the earliest ideas that got me into crypto. I was interested in the curator/art dealer Seth Siegelaub's role in the development of conceptual art. One of his contributions was a royaltee rights contract for secondary art sales. https://t.co/3wXi745lnD https://t.co/27jqiWHGkg

@ourZORA now includes a similar convention, where a content hash of a media object can only be minted once. I also really appreciate their adoption of droit de suite, artist resale rights, which represents a major shift in the economics of art production. https://t.co/D4OPa1trxQ

At the time CryptoPunks & Decentraland had bespoke contracts for non-fungible collections, but while a CryptoPunk price could be triangulated from comparable sales, One Token was a unique edition. The token value was a product of presentation context & viewer's experience alone.

This was a month before CryptoKitties went live, the first Ethereum contract to use the new NFT standard. @dete73 from Axiom Zen also co-authored the EIP. His issue that started it all: https://t.co/LBXD0CJMKb

But BFS for new ideas is just the beginning. DeepTech startups by definition have technologies that are new to you. So you need to dive in via DFS (depth-first search: reading papers, talking to domain experts) to figure out whether it‚Äôs too early, too late, or just right.

Finding the right startup idea (not too late, not too early) requires BFS (breadth-first search) to explore large spaces (for example, posts from leading scientists/entrepreneurs); this is fun and stimulating, and probably what people imagine that VCs do all day. üòõ

To identify these new, converging trends, you by definition need to look beyond traditional vertical or horizontal silos of expertise.  This is why finding early stage startup ideas for DeepTech requires a mix of BFS (breadth-first search) and DFS (depth-first search).

DeepTech is founded on Science & Tech that take decades to refine, so a startup attacking a traditional field faces almost impossible odds versus incumbents.  Instead, look for the ‚Äúconvergence‚Äù of big, established fields in new, unexpected ways (usually driven by data).

DeepTech is hot, but starting or investing in early stage DeepTech startups requires thinking differently. A stellar and expert team is of course critical, but if that's all you focus on, you'll almost certainly be disappointed. You also need Convergence, BFS and DFS. Here's why:

So here is my summary and my warning. Do not trust your life or your family's life to Tesla Autopilot. The chance of it killing you is nonzero, so given enough time, the likelihood of dying if you're not paying attention will trend towards 1.0.#AutonomousDriving #SelfDrivingCar

If Autopilot can't even do the basic stuff, like NOT CRASH INTO VERY LARGE SOLID OBJECTS DIRECTLY IN THE PATH OF MOTION, WITH CLEAR VISIBILITY FROM HUNDREDS OF METERS AWAY, how can we expect it to handle complex situations safely, at least as well as humans??

In Japan a Tesla in Autopilot mode drove full-speed into an overturned truck.https://t.co/i0cuJiFdxhThis completely destroys the argument that Tesla made when Joshua Brown died, that the camera confused the truck with the sky. The system is simply buggy and dangerous!
Similarly, Teslas in Autopilot mode have now crashed into parked firetrucks, not just once but MULTIPLE TIMES. What is more visible than that?https://t.co/LlY7PD5uuz

In 2016 MobilEye Autopilot drove Joshua Brown under a semi, decapitating him. Tesla blamed MobilEye and MobilEye blamed Tesla; the companies parted ways, and Tesla rebuilt everything from the ground up. In 2019 the new Autopilot killed Jeremy Beren Banner in EXACTLY THE SAME WAY.

Heck, for years Autopilot wouldn't even stop for a red light. And it couldn't even stay properly in the middle of the lane without subtly jerking back and forth. How can we trust it to make complex decisions when it can't even do the basics?

It is unconscionable to me that Tesla would try to claim the human was at fault, and not their product, when they actually have the gumption to call the product "Autopilot" even though it's nothing more than a glorified (and buggy) cruise control system.

And in case it needs pointing out, the very first sign of sociopathy is the inability to take personal responsibility. Tesla is a sociopathic company. This comes down from the very top, from Elon himself.

Every time Autopilot kills someone, the Tesla press release lists at least 7 or 8 reasons why Tesla bears no fault for the death (hands weren't on the steering wheel for 8 seconds before the crash, the crash attenuation barrier had not been repaired after a previous crash, ...)

One time back in 2016, I was on an autonomous driving panel with a Tesla engineer. He insisted that Tesla would be at Level 5 autonomy by the end of the year. I told him that was ludicrous. He became very vocal and combative. Autopilot has killed numerous customers since then.

The Tesla s/w development floor sits on the second story of Tesla HQ, above a show floor. Engineers have about 1 meter of desk space each, and hundreds of engineers stand shoulder to shoulder in rows that look like a crowded and noisy Asian sweatshop.

Also when I interviewed at Tesla HQ, I heard many stories about how Elon would frequently order engineers to do things that were scientifically impossible, impossible within his time demands, or ethically sketchy. He would fire people if they didn't meet his demands.

None of this surprises me. I interviewed for the software lead position after the MobilEye split, and I didn't take the job in the end (Andrej took it instead) because I was shocked by the callous and willful ignorance of safety issues of the Tesla team, among other problems.

They would wait and watch to see if any problems arose (via connected telematics), and a team of a couple of engineers would quickly put together back-patches to address any issues that would come up after each release, and they would PUSH THESE UPDATES OUT WITHOUT TESTING.

The Autopilot team would finish a release, push it out to the live vehicles, AND THEY WOULD USE THEIR CUSTOMERS AS THEIR REGRESSION TEST SUITE. Customers, driving their real families, on real roads, in autopilot mode. /...

During the MobilEye days, and even after the complete ground-up rebuild of the hardware under Jim Keller and the software under Andrej Karpathy (both of whom I respect, FWIW), there was ZERO TESTING OF AUTOPILOT RELEASES before they were pushed out. /...

This question bothered me for a while. Why was it tracing out SPY? Why did it go off before the crash? I didn't actually know. I studied, I kept using it on earnings. It was wrong, it was a red herring most likely. Okay. I talked to a ton of smart people. They guessed liquidity.

We then graphed it. I hate graphs, I do not believe in TA. I remember sitting in my parents' kitchen and I saw the graph and I saw side by side it traced out (over time) the same shape as SPY's price graph. Holy shit, okay.

So, bioinformaticians: What have we become? Are we data miners with no concept of ecology? I would hope not. How difficult is it to do the right thing and contact the scientists who work VERY HARD to get the data you are processing?  Give them credit--it's the right thing to do!
The metagenomes were sequenced on Bill Inskeep's CSP @JGI, which includes several related sediment cores from Yellowstone Lake. Neither Bill nor I were ever contacted by the authors.

DNA extraction was not easy and required troubleshooting. I trained an undergraduate student, Matthew Forbes, during the process. Together, we worked hard and acquired high-quality DNA for metagenomic sequencing.

The ROV/ship used to collect these samples cost around $33,000 per day. We had to get permits from the National Park Service and coordinate a massive collaborative effort with geologists, volcanologists, geophysicists, and chemists to work together and collect biological samples.

These authors do not even know what the sample name means. The data aren't presented within any ecological context. "Yellowstone" doesn't even appear in the article, much less Yellowstone Lake, which is where the sequences are from.

DNA sequences that I recovered, still within the 2-yr @JGI data usage embargo, were published yesterday in @ScienceAdvances. I was not an author and I was not acknowledged. The genomes have now been added to @NCBI under completely unrelated author names. This. Is. Wrong.

9/ We hope that this approach will lead to rapid measurement of polymorphic and germline insertion of these elements across the population and advance our understanding of their impact on the human phenotype.

8/ We identify an additional set of 21 non-reference mobile element insertions (16 L1Hs and 5 AluY) that were previously missed in GM12878 by several large-scale studies including Genome in a Bottle and the 1000 Genomes Project. https://t.co/JLG4AFeFMH
7/ We are also able to capture non-reference mobile elements at very high efficiency and demonstrate a saturation of non-reference L1Hs targets at ~30k reads.

6/ We test the efficacy of mobile element discovery using a Flongle and a MinION and then a pooled approach capturing all 5 element types on a MinION. In this last approach we capture 97% L1Hs, 93% AluYb, 51% AluYa, 99% SVA_F, and 65% SVA_E https://t.co/aIH85oJbMh

5/ To address this we apply a modified nCats approach from @timp0 to target the predominant set of mobile elements in the NA12878 human genome: L1Hs, AluYa, AluYb, SVA_E, and SVA_F. We get a remarkable 44% of reads on target! https://t.co/sA6gik4PvT

4/ However, currently active mobile elements are difficult to identify with short read sequencing due to their repetitive nature. And even current long read approaches require whole genome sequencing and are expensive.
3/ We have also recently shown that they have been involved in restructuring the 3D chromatin architecture of the human genome over evolutionary time (and likely still are!): https://t.co/uC4OIV3D8O

2/ Transposable elements are responsible for shaping our genomes and are complicit in sporadic disease, often in neurodevelopmental and neurodegenerative disorders. For a recent review see: https://t.co/KXV2Dr9WY9

1/ Excited to share our targeted Cas9 enrichment and @nanopore sequencing approach to enrich for mobile elements in the genome! Colab w/ @ryan_e_mills @ArthurZhou10 @CamilleMumm @castrocp @drjessswitz These are some highlights: https://t.co/KUgYiGCvAm

We urgently need vaccines that contain antigens (or protein/RNA) *both* for traditional strains and for strains that contain the E484K mutation.

Every strain that develops this mutation effectively forks the virus into two separate diseases, from an immunological point of view, meaning you could catch both versions in quick succession, and the antibodies from one version won't protect you much against the other version.
The fact that this mutation has independently arisen three separate times suggests that the mutation is beneficial to the virus, and soon this mutation will be everywhere.

This is the mutation that is resistant to most of the vaccines so far (the reason being that this mutation flips the charge of one residue in the receptor binding domain of the spike protein, so antibodies cannot bind as strongly).
There is now a third variant, the Bristol variant, that has independently developed the E484K mutation (after the Brazilian and South African variants).https://t.co/y7kCgm74rk

As for why these tapeworms choose different parts of the intestine, we still don't know! An earlier study ruled out competitive exclusion. We think they might be targeting different nutrient but that remains to be shown (more in the MS). Much still to learn about these #parasites

This helps explain why species of Calliobothrium have such a tiny pea-head scolex even though their body is 10x longer than species of Symcallio. The body of the lengthy Calliobothrium tapeworms does a lot of the attachment work

The big surprise was: A NOVEL METHOD OF TAPEWORM ATTACHMENT! The much longer species of Calliobothrium use the serrations on their bodies (laciniations) to lock into dimples on the surfaces of shark villi. This is weird since tapeworms typically attach only with their scolex üòÆ https://t.co/Az1lfqT5KD

We thought they might attach to different parts of the  intestine b/c their attachment organs were specialized for different structures (a pattern seen in other tapeworms). We found that tho the intestinal surface varied in these sharks it WASNT relevant to how the worms attachü§î https://t.co/dgTwfV9anH

Its noteworthy that these genera are very closely related yet morphologically very different. Species of Symcallio are smaller with a larger scolex (attachment organ) while species of Calliobothrium are 10x longer w/ a small scolex & a body serrated with flaps called laciniations https://t.co/F1hXh3E7Zt

The main difference is that species of Symcallio attach at the start of the shark intestine (right after the stomach) while species of the related genus Calliobothrium attach in the middle of the intestine. This pattern is documented in more than 5 species pairs in these genera https://t.co/0DvVCQEcYN

In this @thePeerJ paper we investigated (1) where in the intestine different species of shark #tapeworms attach (2) the surface of the shark intestine (3) how the tapeworms attach to it & (4) why they might consistently choose different regions [t] https://t.co/VgZe5dLXol

Overall, Roseate Tern nest survival was low over the 2 years of our study: only 46% of nests produced a chick that survived >4 days. This is compared to other regions like the NW Atlantic, where nests average >1 chick annually, & could be why the VI population is declining. https://t.co/3lkfw18GPX

We found that nest predation was high & the primary cause of nest failure. Potential predators varied by colony site & included Red-tailed Hawks, but invasive brown rats were main nest predators, followed by (surprisingly!) a Great Egret, then Laughing Gulls. https://t.co/VMv19qVo9I

On these islands, Roseate Tern nests are really variable too, ranging from isolated individuals to dense groups, & from exposed to totally concealed nests. How does all this variation influence egg & chick survival?! And is high nest predation contributing to population declines? https://t.co/7FsdGvGqRL

These colony sites are really different in terms of veg, other seabirds present, human disturbance, & predator presence. Colony sizes are also variable, from 5-700 breeding pairs! More birds at a nest site may = more protection from predators, but also more competition for fish. https://t.co/5djjisIqUy

üßµ: new work out in @AmOrnith! We used #cameratrapping to monitor Roseate Tern nests in 9 colonies in the Virgin Islands. We wanted to know how nest survival & predation risk changed w colony traits, since Caribbean Roseates move nesting islands yearly.https://t.co/4MyySzts0h

The way Alcamy worked; 1/ Create a topic2/ Find a bunch of people who know the subject reasonably well or are in the process of learning it3/ Have them dump all the resources they use to learn; Q/A, videos, pdfs, books etc... into the topic4/ Organize them chronologically https://t.co/lQ3khWGQb7

Next semester, most of my classmates from Chemistry to Comp-sci created quizzes for different courses and we shared them ALL. We had 40+ evergreen topics created that semester. It helped bump all our grades by at least 25% and I didn't even have to write the questions!

I shared it with a few tech-savvy friends and they loved it! Seeing the opportunity, I created Darwin - a simple app that let me crowd-source the whole process! Something that's user-friendly for more people. The first quiz on there was the Biochem Q/A database I created. https://t.co/CtA37vXDDw

b) We were not able to solve the morphological similarity of the species complex; while we failed at this, I think a nice contribution is the recycling of some old ideas on stasis/punctuated equilibrium debate (SJ Gould, N. Eldredge; D. Futuyma; et al.) to cryptic species ...

I applied for smaller funding schemes before - some get funded some got rejected. never got a score or feedback though. this was helpful to see what to focus on next time. looking forward to the next round! üí™
lesson 5: do not limit the feedback just to science - ask what others think about other sections, they make half of the application.

5) dissemination of results is a big part of MSCA and regarding the public engagement part - i said *how* i will communicate my results but didn't say *what* exactly i can communicate about my proposed research. well-detected by the reviewer üò¨
4) my timeline was seen problematic unless collaborations are involved. lesson 4: the project should be ambitious but do not assume you have superpowers üòÖ
either they are wrong or the reviewer didn't know it. lesson 3: follow the secure path. nobody would deduce points if i had discussed sex-dimorphism. but i have just chosen the lazy path.

3)i had a chat with people whose job is to know MSCA guidelines. they said my project doesn't involve human subjects&even though sex-dimorphism is relevant, gender aspects do not apply because gender‚â†sex. so no need to write about it unless my project specifically addresses this

lesson 2: next time, i need to find *multiple* successful applications and read in detail to see what they've done differently. and a public promise, if i ever manage to get funding, just let me know - happy to share my application.

1) the biggest issue was that i didn't have the chance to spend time to go through the text multiple times, get feedback, and see the problems myself before the reviewers did. so lesson 1: start early & get feedback from as much as possible.

still, much to improve next time. i didn't get very detailed feedback but at least the major issues were pointed. tbh now thinking about it i agree with those but didn't even think about some when writing.

in the middle of everything, somewhat unexpected, i decided to apply for this funding with a subject that i tbh do not have much experience but i am very enthusiastic about. i've read a lot & wrote a project that didn't get criticism - which i see as a positive aspect.

i know this but it still hurts. this time- i didn't score high, but i also am not disappointed. i did pretty well last year during the pandemic. wrote&defended my thesis, found an exciting path to follow for my postdoc, finalized an MS, attended&organized many scientific events.

on the contrary to common belief, it's very common to get rejections in academia. manuscripts, job & funding applications.. my understanding is not the ones who never fail become successful but those who learn the lessons and do not become discouraged to try again (#resilience)

To summarise, the term "Biological Process" isn't really helpful as a term in it's own right, but is a useful part of the data structure. Enrichment analysis using GO terms can sometimes be helpful, but the limitations must be clearly understood.

Enrichment analysis with GO terms can sometimes be useful, but primarily as a sanity check (e.g., that gene cluster I think is involved in gametocytogenesis is enriched for GO terms related to meiosis) or a broad hint as to functionality. Just as often, it's not useful.

For non-model organisms this frequently rises to 50% or more. GO term annotation is also biased towards well-studied and conserved functions where transitive annotation is relatively easy, which in turn biases the output of enrichment analysis.

GO terms and enrichment analysis can be useful, but often have severe limitations imposed by the annotation quality of the genome you are working with. As of 2019, almost 1/5 of genes in the human genome had no known function and thus no GO terms.

One use for the DAG is in GO enrichment analysis. Some tools assess each GO term independently, but others take the structure of the ontology into account. An advantage of this is that multiple genes annotated with different terms can result in a significant shared parent term.

The term "Biological Process" could thus be applied to any gene annotated with a term in the BP part of the gene ontology and so is not useful in its own right. However, structuring the ontology as whole as a DAG is useful for traversing the structure and DAGs must have roots.

In most organisms, the convention is that genes are explicitly annotated with only the most specific applicable GO terms, however annotation with less specific parents of the explicit terms can be inferred.
(As aside, DAGs don't have roots and leaves, they have "sources" and "sinks", but I have stuck with terminology that I think will be more widely understood)

Within each part of the gene ontology, all terms except the root have less specific parents and all terms except the terminal leaves have more specific children. "Biological Process" is the root and therefore least specific term in the BP part of the gene ontology.

The Gene Ontology is a controlled way of describing the function of genes and has three parts, Biological Process (BP), Molecular Function (MF) and Cellular Component (CC).  Each of these is a hierarchical data structure (technically a directed acyclic graph (DAG)).

@arneelof @MadsAlbertsen85 @aauengineering @SSI_dk Thx. I know they have been seen. But having the sequences should mean that we don‚Äôt have to guess. I tried to look at https://t.co/xVxf7yIk2land see, I think,2 20H/501Y.V25 20J/501Y.V3and just wondered if someone more knowledgeable than I had looked at the data in detail.

If said analyzes were standard in most papers, we wouldn't be arguing endlessly whether an up-scaler generates white male faces. Everybody would just agree that their Bias Validation goes in that way and be done with it.
If they are, take responsibility and own the results that we get. If they aren't well, we just can agree to have an unbiased model.
I think we need to add new steps to ML models, like the ones with Cross Validation, but another like Bias-Validation, to see if our models are biased towards certain populations.

Perhaps a lot of the effort should be towards just trying and segment the data so that doesn't have as many biases. Like instead of training with a single set for every client, we should train with different sets. Or try and run experiments with different populations.

Perhaps what we need is a new kind of Machine Learning entirely, the current status quo just doesn't afford to make models that make the world as we think it should be. We just don't have data that is clean enough or analyzed enough.

The other side where we have @timnitGebru  and the now twitterless Anima, argues that we need to take responsibility of our models' results and act accordingly to prevent the models from reinforcing the biases that exist in the data.
One side, like the one where we have @pmddomingos and @ylecun argue that messing with the data defeats the purpose of making algorithms that try to predict how the world is going to act.

Thus, Machine Learning, by definition, will be prone towards said data biases. Here is where a lot of people start arguing, whether is the job of scientists to debias the data, or the job of the scientists to design algorithms that don't take into account said biases.

9/ Current lab processing times are inexplicable, & commercial labs must provide quick turnaround. The profit-margin is unconscionable; consumables for RU‚Äôs test are currently $4.34 and headed south. Firms exploiting the vast suffering of others should be held to public account.

8/ Where do we go from here? My read of the evidence is that we should push ‚Äúrelatively rapid‚Äù high sensitivity tests, and take the logistical hurdles head-on rather than knowingly sacrificing lives, or pretending that we aren‚Äôt. America's scientists can step up & help.

7/ We have highly sensitive, simple, at-home tests with same day turnaround, i.e. @RockefellerUniv saliva assay we use on campus. Agree that a challenge for PCR is that samples need to get to the lab; once there fast (3 hr) turnaround can be routine.https://t.co/JZ3noLnp5C

6/ Intra- and inter-lab discrepancies are entirely addressable with basic science/lab/RNA biology principles. We can normalize N1/N2 Ct to RP. In our lab, a 30 in 1 individual is indeed comparable to a 30 in another; controls & QC processes in place ensure that is so.

5/ @michaelmina_lab: Saying a Ct of 30 is meaningless is simply untrue. Yes, Ct values need standards, and current EUA criteria do not normalize, IMHO, to standards.  Fortunately, standards can & should be articulated. I agree they need even more oversight by @DrWoodcockFDA.

4/ Wonkish footnote: To the extent documented, this paper found only a 2-fold increase in transmission going from low to high titer range of ~13-14 Cts (~10^6 to 10^10 viral copies/ml). In other words, people with high Ct values are still infectious!https://t.co/b6o75IitwM

I don't have any specific goals with this project aside from getting something, anything I can eat.I don't care what color or shape they are. I don't care of they're extra spicy or sweet.I just want to have some radishes which are adapted to the conditions I have for them.

I ended up with a decent amount of seed, at least for my purposes. I'll plant them all this year.I don't know if those plants had any genetics which makes them better suited to my growing conditions. It could have just been luck.However, I figure I'd just give them a try.

Most failed miserably. Once they started blooming, I started pulling them out if they had no bulbs. Most didn't.A few produced a decent radish before blooming. I'd written off getting any food from the patch, so those I allowed to go to seed.

Last year I planted a whole mess of radish seeds, from as diverse of sources as I could find. These were commercial seed packs and then a batch from a friend who has grown them a few years.I mixed them all up and planted a patch.

I like radishes, but I've had the poorest time growing them.Our yard has a cold microclimate, staying colder later into spring, then transitioning into warmer weather faster than radishes seem to appreciate.One it gets warm, they flower instead of making me food.

An important lesson here is that model complexity isn't just about the number of estimated parameters in the model. Model complexity is about how 'flexible' it is. LBA trees are frequently estimated because they are more flexible models than non-LBA trees. (end thread)

A similar LBA problem is expected to occur for 'coalescent aware' methods (e.g. ASTRAL) that utilize individual gene/protein tree estimates to get the final topology as shown in: https://t.co/IfLK4UO9Qh

This LBA bias under the correct model can cause problems in concatenated phylogenomic analyses if the data are partitioned by genes, each with its own branchlength parameters. Here the small sample bias compounds into a strongly misleading LBA 'signal' https://t.co/PWlwxrdAuZ
In other words, the model 'space' is larger for the LBA tree than its alternatives and so, with small samples, it has a higher chance to be selected as the ML tree.

I guess coming back full circle, I admit that I've made an active effort to hide my learning disabilities throughout my life because I know how hard my brother's life has been (I never went to disability services after my college advisor's advice for this reason).

He recently completed his Associate's degree (we're 2.5 years apart) and is so worried about how his disabilities are interfering and keeping him "behind". This really makes me sad, because he's doing great. ie He has one of the highest EQs of many I know, and that's not easy.

His comments on it is that people don't understand because they don't have to experience it first-hand, and that hopefully they've had time to reflect on their past behaviors and grow. Like is said, he's incredible generally.

Seeing my brother go through all of this definitely has made me a more empathic person than if he was abled. The more impressive thing about him is that he doesn't even hold any ill will towards people who've bullied him or treated him badly, even though he has every reason.

Through the years, my brother was bullied for his speech impediment. And adults would also get frustrated in not being able to understand him. I would act as a 'translator' when I could. Honestly, it was hard to watch a lot of the time, and of course harder for him to experience.

My brother has physical and learning disabilities (I have permission from him to share this), and his life has been very hard. People treat him differently, and often treat him as useless (including our own family). My brother is incredibly intelligent, and incredible generally.

An absorbed photon will excite an electron between t2g and eg orbitals within the complex. The energy required to permit that transition is what dictates the color of the absorbed and transmitted/reflected light.... and that‚Äôs as far as my inorganic knowledge takes me haha

A photon of light will be absorbed by the complex if it has an energy equivalent to what is needed to excite an electron with in the complex. For copper sulfate, that energy is in reddish light, which means the crystal will appear blue because blue is not absorbed.

The Cu in copper sulfates has lost 2 of its electrons and has a 2+ charge.The sulfate ions and water molecules are both attracted to the positive charge on the Cu(II) and coordinate it in a octahedral orientation.

The reason I bring this up is to discuss the color of Chalcanthite (CuSO4‚Ä¢5H2O), which stems from the kinds of bonds this particular flavor of Cu ion forms with sulfate ions and water molecules in its crystal lattice. You can stop here if you want üòÖ https://t.co/fHge7nSXfv
